item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - DenverParty for Socialism and Liberation - PSL

üó£Ô∏è On this day in 1973, a U.S.-engineered military coup led by Augusto Pinochet deposed Chile‚Äôs democratically-elected socialist president, Salvador Allende, an...d ushered in a fascist regime that killed tens of thousands of Chileans.

On the morning of Sept. 11, 1973, as tanks and personnel carriers circled the presidential palace in Santiago, Pinochet‚Äôs forces fired into the palace while planes dropped bombs. Allende and a core of his staff resisted until the fascist troops stormed the building. Allende was killed.

By afternoon, all government offices in the country were taken over. Within weeks, thousands of leftists, intellectuals, unionists and supporters of Allende were rounded up and tortured in the National Stadium. Many were executed. Congress was suspended, unions and political parties banned, and habeas corpus eliminated.

Among these desparecidos was famous Communist poet and singer Victor Jara. Born into poverty to a peasant family, by the age of 6 Jara was already working on a farm. Yet he became a distinguished theater director and played a pivotal role in establishing the Nueva Canci√≥n Chilena movement.

Before Jara was murdered, soldiers smashed his fingers and then mocked him, handed him a guitar and forced him to play a song. In a display of immense revolutionary resilience, with broken hands Jara sang the song that was the anthem of the movement, Venceremos ‚Äì We Will Triumph. Jara‚Äôs life was brutally taken by army lieutenant Pedro Pablo Barrientos. Barrientos who played Russian roulette with Jara until a shot finally rang out. He was then shot another 44 times, and his body dumped in the street along with the hundreds of others.

In his final hours, Jara composed one last song on a scrap of paper. The song ends, ‚ÄúHow hard it is to sing when I must sing of horror... What I see, I have never seen, what I have felt and what I feel, will give birth to the moment.‚Äù

Victor Jara‚Äôs legacy will live on forever in his music and perseverance. No amount of guns, tanks, prisons, or unjust laws can stop the movement towards justice.

item.title: Justice for Antonio Blackbear, shot to death by Denver Police...
item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

Justice for Antonio Blackbear, shot to death by Denver Police this Wednesday, September 9. Antonio is the seventh person fatally shot by DPD this year, and the cousin of Paul Castaway, who was murdered by Denver Police in 2015.

The racist violence of the police against our community has not let up, even in the midst of a nationwide protest movement putting a spotlight on their brutality. If our communities are ever to be safe, we have to keep fighting and building the movement for justice and against the racist police and the system they serve.

item.title: ‚ÄúScientists have a hard time predicting exactly how fast...
item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

‚ÄúScientists have a hard time predicting exactly how fast climate change will unfold and the extent of the effects. We are currently only at 1 C warming and already experiencing extreme weather and devastation around the globe. The much-touted Paris Agreement‚Äôs voluntary commitments have us on target for 3 C warming, when scientists warn that staying below 1.5 C warming is what is needed to avert catastrophe.

Despite being in charge of the wealthiest country in the world, the... U.S. government ‚Äî Democrat and Republican ‚Äî is doing nothing to mitigate or prepare for the looming catastrophe. Even in the liberal bastion of California, state leadership is not taking the crisis seriously. California is the fifth largest economy in the world, yet there is no money for people‚Äôs needs while Big Tech gets tax breaks.

If humanity is to survive this crisis, we must immediately put all resources into preparing for what‚Äôs currently unfolding and what‚Äôs to come. We must immediately transition off fossil fuels and restore ecosystems that capture carbon from the atmosphere. We must protect the population from climate disasters and provide real relief for people in the aftermath.

Capitalism has proven time and again that it is incapable and unwilling to meet the needs of the people. If we don‚Äôt uproot the system that has created the climate crisis, that continues to ignore it and go about business as usual, the majority of us face a truly dire not-too-distant future. The people have the power to change the path we are on ‚Äî to share the challenges together and build a better world for all.‚Äù

item.title: Yesterday some 1500 community members marched on foot and in...
item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

Yesterday some 1500 community members marched on foot and in their cars down Colfax from Aurora to Denver against racism and police violence. People all along the march came out of their homes and shops and stopped on the streets to watch and show their support. Families from across the state who have had their loved ones murdered by the police came to speak and march with us.

People all over this country are tired of the racism and the brutality of life under this system. They are ready for change! The future lies in the hands of the people! Together we will one day crush this racist system and build one that works for all of us!

Keep building, keep fighting! All power to the people!

item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

Today we honor Fred Hampton on what would have been his 72nd birthday.

Fred Hampton was a young revolutionary socialist and chairman of the Black Panther Party in Chicago.

Hampton was a community-builder. He brokered a nonaggression pact between Chicago‚Äôs most powerful street gangs, urging them to turn their anger and guns around on their oppressors, not on one another.

item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

Revolutionary women of the PSL on the frontlines of the struggle ‚úäüö©

Party for Socialism and Liberation - PSL

In celebration of the 10th issue of Breaking the Chains magazine, we want to showcase the amazing women who not only create this magazine but also put theory in...to practice by organizing in the streets! From Los Angeles to Boston, women are on the frontlines of the rebellion against racism and police violence. As unemployment and COVID-19 cases continue to rise, women have shown that they are not only essential workers but are essential to revolution! We will continue to mobilize in the streets and build towards a feminist and socialist future, because the struggle for women's liberation is part and parcel of the liberation of ALL workers!

item.title: Check out the Denver Police Department putting on an ice cream...
item.content:encoded:
Party for Socialism and Liberation - Denver

Check out the Denver Police Department putting on an ice cream social to draw parents and kids out to meet "Officer Friendly". It's more important than ever to the police to do PR with the parts of the community disconnected enough from their brutality to believe they're really here to "protect and serve".

The truth is that DPD is not family-friendly. They are not sweet or cuddly. Denver police murdered William Debose, Paul Childs, Dion Damon, Michael Marshall, Jason Gomez, J...esse Hernandez, Marvin Booker, Paul Castaway, Ryan Ronquillo, Joseph Valverde, Odiceo Valencia-Lopez, Naeschylus Carter-Vinzant, and many more. They have brutalized countless members of our community and put many more behind bars. They have spent the summer brutally repressing the anti-racist protest movement.

These PR stunts are repulsive, but they will not be enough to stop the advance of consciousness around the true nature of the police.
